    <theorem xml:id="th_A5_isomorphism">
    <title>Unique simple group of cardinality 60</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>G</m> be a group of cardinality <m>60</m>. If <m>G</m> is simple, then <m>G\cong A_5</m>. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
    <p>
    </p>
    </proof>
    </theorem>
    <corollary xml:id="cor_isos_symmetries">
        <title>Group of rotational symmetries of the dodecahedron</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>D</m> be a regular dodecahedron in <m>\R^3</m>, and let <m>G</m> be its group of rotational symmetries. We have <m>G\cong A_5</m>. 
            </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
            <p>
                The regular dodecahedron has <m>12</m> pentagonal faces, <m>30</m> edges, and <m>20</m> vertices. Consider the action of <m>G</m> on the set <m>F</m> of faces of <m>D</m>. It is easy to see that this action is transitive, and that the stabilizer <m>G_F</m> of any given face <m>F</m> consists of the rotations of degree <m>2\pi k/5</m> about the axis passing through the centers of that face and its opposite face. It follows from the orbit-stabilizer theorem that
                <me>
                    \abs{G}=\abs{O_{F}}\abs{G_F}=12\cdot 5=60
                </me>.
                Furthermore, since <m>G</m> contains such rotations of order <m>5</m> for each of the 6 pairs of opposite faces, we see that it has at least <m>24</m> elements of order <m>5</m>. It follows that <m>n_5(G)\ne 1</m>. We conclude from <xref ref="th_card_60_simple"/> that <m>G</m> is simple, and from <xref ref="th_A5_isomorphism"/> that <m>G\cong A_5</m>.
            </p>
        </proof>
    </corollary>

